2. Updated Algorithm: Recency-Weighted with Survival Bias Correction
2.1  Eligibility Window
Only AOR cohorts from the dynamic cutoff date onwards are used to compute estimates. The cutoff is computed each weekly sync using the formula in §8b (cutoff_date = today − clamp(1.5 × stored_median, 270, 547)). As of May 2026 this resolves to approximately Jul 5, 2025. Earlier cohorts are archived for historical reference but excluded from active predictions.

Eligible cohorts
AOR_date >= cutoff_date (dynamic — see §8b)
Cutoff auto-adjusts weekly with stored median


2.2  Survival Bias Correction
For any cohort where applicants are still waiting, the algorithm imputes a projected completion date rather than ignoring them. The imputation uses a conservative lower bound: current days elapsed + 30 days minimum. This prevents the median from being pulled down by the fast completers who are visible, while the slower completers who are invisible drive the true average higher.

Imputed days
days_elapsed_so_far + 30
For each still-waiting applicant


Corrected median
MEDIAN(completed_days ∪ imputed_days)
Combined distribution


Why +30 days?
30 days is a conservative lower bound. A still-waiting applicant cannot receive eCOPR in the past — so their true completion day is at minimum today. Adding 30 days acknowledges that processing doesn't resolve overnight. In practice, many slow-lane cases wait 60-120+ additional days, so this correction is conservative and the real median is likely higher.


2.3  Recency Weighting
Within the eligible window, more recent eCOPR completions receive higher weight. This is implemented by giving 2x weight to completions in the trailing 90 days. The effect: a sudden slowdown or speedup in IRCC processing appears in estimates within 4-6 weeks rather than being diluted by older data.

